<section class="card">
  <h2>Direct Answer</h2>

  <p>
    <strong>In most Zone 5 locations, tomatoes should be started indoors about 6–8 weeks before the last spring frost.</strong>
    If you are within that window, it is not too late.
  </p>

  <p>
    If you are past that window, you may still succeed with:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Early-maturing varieties (60–70 days)</li>
    <li>Strong light during seedling growth</li>
    <li>Prompt transplanting after frost risk declines</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Why Zone 5 Is Only a Starting Point</h2>

  <p>
    USDA Zone 5 generally experiences:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Average last frost: mid-April to mid-May</li>
    <li>Average first fall frost: late September to mid-October</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Comparable cold-climate regions in Canada follow similar frost timelines.
  </p>

  <p>
    Frost dates vary within the zone, so always use your local average rather than relying on the zone label alone.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Tomato Timing in Zone 5</h2>

  <p>
    Tomatoes need:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>6–8 weeks indoors before transplant</li>
    <li>Nighttime lows above 50°F (10°C) for strong growth</li>
    <li>Soil temperatures around 60°F (16°C) for root establishment</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    In Zone 5, transplanting often occurs from mid-May through early June,
    depending on the specific frost date.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>When It May Actually Be Too Late</h2>

  <p>
    It may be too late to start tomatoes if:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Your first fall frost is less than 90–100 days away</li>
    <li>You plan to grow long-season varieties (80+ days)</li>
    <li>Seedlings will not reach transplant size before warm weather peaks</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    In short-season regions, lost time early is difficult to recover.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>What to Do If You’re Starting Late</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Choose early-maturing varieties</li>
    <li>Provide strong indoor light</li>
    <li>Transplant promptly once frost risk declines</li>
    <li>Avoid transplanting into repeated cool nights below 50°F (10°C)</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    For transplant timing logic, review
    <a href="/guides/when-to-transplant-seedlings-outdoors/">When to Transplant Seedlings Outdoors</a>.
  </p>
</section>

